Analysis of the effects of the 2017 Travel Ban Executive order¶

By Austin Chi, Vuong Nguyen, and Spencer Phillips¶

We were curious what some of the effects of the 2017 Travel Ban executive order signed by President Donald Trump on individuals and wanted to answer a few specific questions.

1. Looking at the 7 countries targeted by the ban, how many people would be refused greencards over a 90 day period? What proportion would be refugees?
-howandwheregreencard.xls
Assume refugee applicants for 2017 are roughly the same as 2015 and the applicants are distributed iid Uniformly over the year.

2. With Refugees, where do they come from? What country brings the highest proportion of refugees vs Green Card holders? Do these countries have more refugees than others on average?
-HowAndWhereGreenCard.xls
Plot on map showing number of immigrants and proportion of immigrants that are refugees.

3. How many of these individuals would be deported? How many for doing illegal things?
-RemovedByCrimAndNationality.xls

4.Analysis public sentiment for the ban.
Twitter API for public sentiment.

We asked these to see more into what this ban would do to the United States as a whole using data from 2015 from the US Department of Homeland Security. This data will be analyzed through pandas and visualized in different ways.

Packages Used¶

First the packages we are going to be using will include pandas and numpy for organizing our data, matplotlib in order to graph things and using the gg plot style. The ttest_ind will be used for our t test later on in the analysis which is important to look at. The "Austin" package was created by Austin in order to save our tables to an sqllite file and is also used in the scraping of Twitter later on to form our overarching dataset for our analysis later on. Basemap, Polygon, Normalize, and PatchCollection is used in the formation of our maps later on for visualization.

Working with the DHS data¶

First we need to take the DHS data and put it into a dataframe. In the excel doc, values with a D are nondisclosed values for secrecy, so we made those into NAs and also made it so there are Trues and Falses for if the country is considered banned or not in the collumn 'banned'. There is also a column called 'refugee_to_total' which will have the proportion of green card holders that are refugees. All relevant collumns are turned into np.float values in order to be used on each other. Country of birth is changed to country for the mapping later on.

In [2]:
greencard = pd.read_excel('HowAndWhereGreenCard.xls',sheetname='Country',
              skiprows=[0,1,2], skip_footer=4,na_values = ['D'])
greencard['refugee_to_total']=''
greencard['banned']=''
greencard['Total'] = greencard['Total'].astype(np.float64)
bannedcount = ['Iran','Iraq','Libya','Somalia', 'Sudan','Syria','Yemen']
for x in xrange(len(greencard)):
    if greencard['Country of birth'][x] in bannedcount:
        greencard['banned'][x] = True
    else:
        greencard['banned'][x] = False
for x in xrange(len(greencard)): 
    greencard['refugee_to_total'][x]=greencard['Refugees and asylees'][x]/greencard['Total'][x]
greencard['refugee_to_total']=greencard['refugee_to_total'].astype(np.float)
greencard.rename(columns={'Country of birth':'country'}, inplace=True)

Here is where we answer question 1¶

Here is the answer to our first question asking how many people would be effected by the ban. In this we assume that the overall number of people entering the country over the year is iid, which we will also look at below, so we just divide the total number by 4 to see our overall number of individuals effected

Here we will test if things are actually iid using data from the US Department of State on 2015 per month refugee arrivals.

This shows that our predictions will be fairly liberal since the months the travel ban would take place, January, February, and March, are some of the slower months with September being the main month for refugees to come into the country. This is shown by having the sum of January to March be significantly less than the sum divided by 4. Also, we are working with refugee numbers here, not green card numbers. These also are for the whole world coming to the US, not just the banned nations. As well, this is data from the US Department of State which may have different metrics to get their data than the US DHS.

We first see that this would prevent about 13,000 individuals from getting green cards to come to this country regardless of their status and would leave about 8,000 refugees unable to get green cards as they live in one of the banned nations. This is about 61% of all of the green card recipients from the banned nations.
From this we see that this would lead to 10 less individuals removed from the country if the countries were banned. This is only 0.029% of the total of pepople removed in that 3 month time period! In the end, it would be more effective to focus on other countries if you want to decrease criminals since these do not have many removed.

In [16]:
scipy.stats.mannwhitneyu(truesgreen['refugee_to_total'], falsesgreen['refugee_to_total'])
Out[16]:
MannwhitneyuResult(statistic=335.0, pvalue=0.011808980415347741)

Above we see a t-test between the trues and false's to find out if there is a significant difference between the two. First though, there is one major issue over the two having massive differences in sample sizes with the banned countries only having 7 vs the nonbanned countries having 193 data points. This comes with an issue of a high type II error rate. We do get a t stat of 4.249 with a p-value of .000054914 meaning that we reject the null that they are equal and conclude that they are not equal to each other and that there is a difference between the banned and unbanned nations refugee proportions. Due to the crazy assumptions we decided to do a Mann Whitney test as well. We get a p-value of 0.01180898 which is still significant.This agrees with our above result that rejects the null and concludes that they do have not the same amount of refugees comng from these countries.

Above is a t-test comparing the 'proportion_crim' from the True and False to each other. Again we face the issue of the nonbanned nations having 193 and the banned coutnries having 7. Austin Package for Twitter Scraping¶

Below is the package 'Austin' (created by Austin obviously) that was used for the 'save_game' function that we saw above and the scraping of Twitter that was built around the tweepy package. We will go over each function here:

  • The "save_game" function which takes a Pandas dataframe and saves it as an sqlite database and names it as the date
  • The Auth is the creation of a class which takes the API keys needed to scrape twitterand puts them all together.
  • StreamSaver takes the dataframe from Twitter and then appends it to the sqlite file. It also prints the tweet but this it turned off for long term use since it caused python to overload and the code to just stop.
  • createconnectiontostreamer takes in the APIs and puts it into the stream which is used to start up the function and log in.
  • streamrestarter is how we start the scraping and it uses the previous 2 and save_game to make the sqlite file. We found when running that some errors occurred over time for strange reasons which we assumed were because we were getting kicked out due to taking too much data. We made it then that if we got errors the program would run again unless a keyboard interupt made it stop. We also put in a 5 second cooldown between errors to not overload things as well.

def save_game(df,overwrite = "none",append = False):
    """Saves Pandas Dataframe to sqlite database. Takes in Pandas Dataframe and name of database(optional). 
    Defualt name is the date."""
    if overwrite != "none":
        engine = create_engine('sqlite:///'+overwrite+'.sqlite')
        if  append == True:
            df.to_sql('table',engine,if_exists='append')
        else:
            df.to_sql('table',engine,if_exists='replace')
            print "You have succesfully saved!"
        return
    else :
        name = str(datetime.datetime.now().date()).replace(" ","").replace("-","").replace(":","").replace(".","")
        enginename = 'sqlite:///%s.sqlite' % name
        engine = create_engine(enginename)
        if append == True:
            df.to_sql('table',engine,if_exists='append')
        else:
            df.to_sql('table',engine,if_exists='replace')
            print "You have succesfully saved!"
        return

class StreamSaver(tweepy.StreamListener):
    def on_status(self, status):
        temp = {"User" : status.user.screen_name,"Text" : status.text,"Coord" : status.coordinates,"Time" : status.created_at}
        tempdf = pd.DataFrame([temp])

def createconnectiontostreamer(a):
    """a is an Auth() object"""
    auth = tweepy.OAuthHandler(a.API_KEY, a.API_SECRET)
    auth.set_access_token(a.TWITTER_KEY, a.TWITTER_SECRET)
    api = tweepy.API(auth)
    stream_saver = StreamSaver()
    stream = tweepy.Stream(auth = api.auth, listener = stream_saver)
    return stream

def streamrestarter(a,listofsearch = ["muslim ban","travel ban"]):
    """a is auth object (get from createconnectiontostreamer()), 
    listofsearch is list of search terms. """
    try:
        createconnectiontostreamer(a).filter(track=listofsearch)
        return
    except KeyboardInterrupt:
        createconnectiontostreamer(a).disconnect()
        return
    except:
        print "ERROR! RESTARTING IN 5 SECONDS!"
        time.sleep(5)
        streamrestarter(a,listofsearch)
        return

Twitter Sentiment Analysis¶

We will be taking a look at sentiments in terms of supporting or opposing Donald Trump's highly controversial travel ban. The process of analyzing public sentiments involes a few steps. First off, considering that tweets are generally highly disorganized in terms of grammar and structure, some preprocessing is necessary. For the most parts, links given in tweets are useless for analysis since the classifying algorithm will only deal with the main body of text. At tags (@) will also be removed as they may not provide consistent information (a proponent or an opponent could tweet at somebody). The clean_text() function will be the main driver of the preprocessing. Tokenization/Lemmatization is done witht he nltk's WordNetLemmatizer. Also, the built-in nltk english stop words list is modified in order to filter out commonly occurring uniformative words(features). This includes the search terms which were used to stream tweets. The clean_text function was used accordingly on the training sample as well as the random sample for 10,000 tweets. Then, they are saved to 2 excel files for ease of access and saving time.

Next comes the training process where we randomly sampled from the total tweets (~1.5million) and manually classified them. The total training data came out to be just under 800 tweets. Since we are using the Naive Bayes classifier, the training data must be formatted in a particular way. This is formatted as a list of 2-tuples where the first element is the list of tokens of the tweet and the second element is the category of sentiment. The basic idea is to compile a list of the top 1000 most commonly occuring words from the training data and save them as the features with which we train the algorithm to distinguish between positive or negative. This is done based on probabilities for certain features to appear in positive vs. negative sentiments. We found an accuracy rate of around 80%. This figure is subject to variability considering the limitations of training data as well as the rudimentary nature of the algorithm.

Considering the immense size of our streamed data, we resorted to randomly sampling 10,000 tweets from the database and classifying these. We found with this sample, 1437 out of the 10,000 tweets were in support of the travel ban. This is only a rough figure since there are many factors not considered which are beyond the scope of this analysis. For example, accounting for relevance might be an issue since the search terms may return unrelated tweets. However, overall we do see a majority of the tweets concerning this topic lean towards negativity.

#modifying the built-in nltk english stop words list
eng_stop_mod = list(stopwords.words('english'))
for e in string.printable:
    if not e.isalpha(): #everything not alpha character
        eng_stop_mod.append(e)
eng_stop_mod = eng_stop_mod + ['trump', 'ban', 'muslim', 'rt','travel',"'s",'amp']

tokenize = nltk.word_tokenize #nltk tokenizer
lemma = WordNetLemmatizer().lemmatize #nltk WordNetLemmatizer
def lemmatize(text): #function to make it work for a whole text
    return [lemma(tok.lower()) for tok in tokenize(text)]

def clean_text(text_list):
    '''
    Removes links, @tags, takes care of troubling characters, stop words
    from a list of texts (tweets)
    '''
    cleaned = []
    for text in text_list:
        text = re.sub(r"htt\S+", "", text)
        text = re.sub('@\S+', '', text)
        text = text.translate({ 0x2018:0x27, 0x2019:0x27, 0x201C:0x22, 0x201D:0x22, 0x2026:0x20 })
        text = ' '.join(e for e in lemmatize(text) if e not in eng_stop_mod)
        cleaned.append(text)
    return cleaned

all_words = [] #compile list of all words from training text
for text in train.Text:
    for w in tokenize(text):
        all_words.append(w)
#some filtering for non alpha characters/insignificant chars/words
all_words = [''.join(ch for ch in c if ch.isalpha() or ch == ' ') for c in all_words]
all_words = [e for e in all_words if e != '' and len(e) > 2]
all_words = nltk.FreqDist(all_words) #frequency dist. of all words 

word_feats = [] #grabbing top 1000 most frequent words
for i in all_words.most_common(1000):
    word_feats.append(i[0])

#finding the features in form of dictionary(for each of 1000 top words: whether it exists in a text)
def find_feats(item):
    words = set(item) #exclue duplicates
    features = {} 
    for w in word_feats:
        features[w] = (w in words)
    return features

def classify_tweet(tweet): 
    '''
    classify each tweet(give the sentiment)
    '''
    #find the features for each tweet first
    feat = find_feats(tokenize(tweet))
    #classify using those features
    return classifier.classify(feat)

Conclusion¶

In conclusion, we see from the DHS data that many thousands of individuals will be prevented from getting into the country over those 3 months and that while these countries bring in more refugees than non banned nations, they do not bring an more criminal immigrants into the country compared to other countries. When we ran to check the information on twitter against the travel ban, we saw that people were not supporting it on the large scale. We would like to say this is because there are not many criminals coming from the countries that are banned and partially due to political throwback against the current administration.
